  "answer": "## Answer\nThe main failure modes of memory in LLM agents are best understood as a pipeline problem, not just \"forgetting\":\n\n- **Access failures**: the needed information is not available in the active context, or it is hard to use when buried in the middle of a long prompt. This is a core limitation of standard LLM context handling and shows up as positional bias in long-context retrieval. See `https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.08560` and `https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.03172`. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.08560))\n- **Retrieval / matching failures**: the system retrieves the wrong memory, or a superficially similar memory that is actually misleading. Empirically, memory-management choices can produce error propagation and misaligned experience replay. See `https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.16067`. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.16067))\n- **Update / consolidation failures**: the agent keeps obsolete memories, fails to reconcile new information with old memory, or handles contradictions poorly. Recent survey and benchmark work call out continual consolidation, contradiction handling, and reuse of invalid memories as open problems. See `https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.07670` and `https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.20006`. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.07670))\n- **Corruption / governance failures**: memory can drift semantically during iterative summarization, and sensitive context can leak into long-term storage. See `https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11768`. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11768))\n\nA compact way to say it is: **LLM agent memory fails when it cannot access the right information, retrieves the wrong information, fails to update or retire old information, or corrupts information while storing it**. That synthesis is grounded in the sources above. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.08560))\n\n## Sources\n- MemGPT: Towards LLMs as Operating Systems — `https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.08560`. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.08560))\n- Lost in the Middle: How Language Models Use Long Contexts — `https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.03172`. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.03172))\n- How Memory Management Impacts LLM Agents: An Empirical Study of Experience-Following Behavior — `https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.16067`. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.16067))\n- Memory for Autonomous LLM Agents: Mechanisms, Evaluation, and Emerging Frontiers — `https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.07670`. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.07670))\n- Governing Evolving Memory in LLM Agents: Risks, Mechanisms, and the Stability and Safety Governed Memory (SSGM) Framework — `https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11768`. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11768))\n- From Recall to Forgetting: Benchmarking Long-Term Memory for Personalized Agents — `https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.20006`. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.20006))\n\n## Limitations\nThis is a synthesis across a small set of recent primary papers, not a standardized taxonomy. The literature does **not** yet use one universal naming scheme for memory failures, and the relative importance of each failure mode depends on the agent design, memory architecture, and benchmark. I also did not find a source that gives a single cross-domain prevalence ranking for these failure modes. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.07670))"
